00:36:09.860 --> 00:36:13.320
There's got to be some
sort of radioactive decay.

00:36:13.320 --> 00:36:17.120
So what are our
choices of particles?

00:36:17.120 --> 00:36:17.620
Yep?

00:36:17.620 --> 00:36:19.060
AUDIENCE: An electron.

00:36:19.060 --> 00:36:19.893
MICHAEL SHORT: Sure.

00:36:19.893 --> 00:36:20.710
An electron.

00:36:20.710 --> 00:36:24.790
Or more specifically, we'll
call it a beta particle.

00:36:24.790 --> 00:36:26.830
Just like a gamma
ray is a photon that

00:36:26.830 --> 00:36:29.380
originates in the
nucleus, a beta particle

00:36:29.380 --> 00:36:31.750
is an electron that
originates in a nucleus.

00:36:31.750 --> 00:36:35.020
You can't tell it's a beta
particle just by looking at it.

00:36:35.020 --> 00:36:36.640
An electron is an electron.

00:36:36.640 --> 00:36:39.580
The only way you'd know
is either by its energy,

00:36:39.580 --> 00:36:42.640
or by because they're another
source of electrons nearby.

00:36:42.640 --> 00:36:48.055
So in this case,
we get beta decay.

00:36:48.055 --> 00:36:49.180
This looks fairly balanced.

00:36:52.510 --> 00:36:54.940
One thing that I'll
put in is beta decay

00:36:54.940 --> 00:36:57.790
is accompanied by
an antineutrino,

00:36:57.790 --> 00:36:59.560
but I did not expect
anyone to know that.

00:36:59.560 --> 00:37:02.000
I just wanted to make sure
it's up there for completeness.

00:37:02.000 --> 00:37:05.860
So what we're relying
on is the movement

00:37:05.860 --> 00:37:10.210
of these electrons, which are
high charge and low mass, which

00:37:10.210 --> 00:37:11.920
means they're very low range.

00:37:11.920 --> 00:37:14.500
Which means when you
implant a brachytherapy seed

00:37:14.500 --> 00:37:17.470
into a person, the
irradiation volume

00:37:17.470 --> 00:37:20.950
is only as large as the
energy of that beta particle

00:37:20.950 --> 00:37:22.330
will allow.

00:37:22.330 --> 00:37:24.760
The maximum energies
for these beta particles

00:37:24.760 --> 00:37:27.520
are given by the differences
between the starting

00:37:27.520 --> 00:37:29.450
and the ending energy.

00:37:29.450 --> 00:37:31.060
The way these diagrams
are constructed

00:37:31.060 --> 00:37:33.910
is your ending energy is
usually at an energy of zero,

00:37:33.910 --> 00:37:37.090
which we refer to as the
ground state of that isotope.

00:37:37.090 --> 00:37:39.450
And all of these are
relative energies

00:37:39.450 --> 00:37:41.920
in MeV, or megaelectron volts.

00:37:41.920 --> 00:37:46.360
So for example, this
iridium-192 has a 40% chance

00:37:46.360 --> 00:37:50.800
of decaying by beta
to platinum-192,

00:37:50.800 --> 00:37:56.380
which means the electron
can have up to 1.4597 MeV.

00:37:56.380 --> 00:37:59.980
And if we know its energy,
we know its maximum range.

00:37:59.980 --> 00:38:02.710
So selecting the right
isotope and the right activity

00:38:02.710 --> 00:38:04.870
for the right tumor
is quite important.

00:38:04.870 --> 00:38:06.550
Notice that there's
also other ways

00:38:06.550 --> 00:38:08.410
in which this thing can decay.

00:38:08.410 --> 00:38:11.710
It might release a beta
particle of a lower energy

00:38:11.710 --> 00:38:16.510
and reach what's called an
excited state of platinum-192,

00:38:16.510 --> 00:38:20.440
which can then decay by just
giving off this extra 612

00:38:20.440 --> 00:38:23.248
keV of energy to
the ground state.

00:38:23.248 --> 00:38:24.790
So let's write that
nuclear reaction.

00:38:24.790 --> 00:38:29.920
Let's say we have
platinum-192, and I'll

00:38:29.920 --> 00:38:39.020
put a star to mention that it's
excited, becomes platinum-192.

00:38:39.020 --> 00:38:40.804
Where did the energy go?

00:38:40.804 --> 00:38:41.637
AUDIENCE: Gamma ray.

00:38:41.637 --> 00:38:42.512
MICHAEL SHORT: Gamma.

00:38:42.512 --> 00:38:43.832
